<lb corresp="#a5"/><w>k</w><w>tuseñc-äṃ</w><pc>•</pc><w>säm</w><w>neṣ</w><w>nākṣāt</w><w>kāṣiññā<supplied>t</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<w><supplied>ña</supplied><lb corresp="#a6"/>reyaṃ</w><pc>:</pc><w>ṣuṅkäṣ</w><w>poryo</w><w>tsäknäṣtär</w><w>tsā</w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b1"/><w>ñareyntwaṃ</w><pc>:</pc><num value="1">1</num><pc>॥</pc><w>pärskont</w><w>akmalyo</w><w>śri</w><gap reason="lost"/>
<w><supplied>ku</supplied><lb corresp="#b2"/>rsärwāyo</w><w>kUcā-eṣäk-ne</w><w>upādhyā</w><w>ca</w><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b3"/><w>ñ<gap reason="plain" unit="part"/>äṣ</w><w>poṣi</w><w>täṣ</w><w>weñe<supplied>ñc</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b4"/><gap reason="plain" quantity="4"/><w>m<gap reason="plain" unit="part"/>ārṣe</w><w><gap reason="plain" unit="part"/>e</w><gap reason="lost"/></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the ax ... that. Having cut off the ho(pe) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... they kindle him/it. Previously this one blamed [and] scolded (others) ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Früher tadelte [und] schalt er ...</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">Previously he scolded [and] rebuked.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>172</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:kolver1965"/><citedRange>23</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... in the (hell) ... From the throat by means of fire he burns [and] (he is stabbed?) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... in the hells. 1. With fearful face NN ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>336</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... over [very] many miles, over which the teacher ... th(is) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... from the (body?) this [is] the side/surface, (they) will say ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... </seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="remarks">The left part of a leaf with rest of the string hole space covering lines 3 and 4; lines a1-2 and b5-6 are lost.</note><note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment"><hi>ktuseñc-äṃ</hi> is rather not a 3.pl. present from the root <hi>katw</hi>- 'to ridicule', but an s-present from the root <w lemmaRef="E_A_tuwā_G"/> 'to kindle'.</note><note corresp="#a6" type="philcomment"><hi>tsā</hi> is probably the beginning of a present form of <w lemmaRef="E_A_tsākā_G"/> 'to pierce'. The visible remains of the following sign speaks in favor of that.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment"><hi>śri</hi> is most likely the beginning of a proper name.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="lingcomment">The use of the instr. with <hi>kursär</hi> possibly indicates a huge distance; cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>28</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment"><hi>ca</hi> is probably <hi>caṣ</hi>; the last akṣara is a complex ligatura, probably with a vowel <hi>u</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">Below the <hi>ñ</hi> of <hi>ñäṣ</hi> may be another sign, which could be a) <hi>c</hi> making it a 3.sg. verbal form <hi>(lä)ñcäṣ</hi>, or b) <hi>ñ</hi>, in which case we would have <hi>(kapśi)ñ(ñ)äṣ</hi> 'from the body'. A possible restoration for <hi>weñe</hi> would be a form of the subjunctive of <hi>weñ</hi>- or the form has to be separated differently into <hi>we ñe(mi?)</hi>, though the latter is not very likely.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">Segmentation uncertain.</note></p>
         </div>
